  "prompt": "What are the legal precedents related to money laundering cases?",
  "response": "There are various legal precedents related to money laundering, including cases involving financial institutions, criminal enterprises, and regulatory enforcement. Notable cases include:\n\n1. United States v. Bank of Credit and Commerce International (BCCI)\n- Major international banking fraud case\n- Involved global money laundering activities\n- Led to significant regulatory reforms\n\n2. United States v. Turkette (1981)\n- Supreme Court case defining criminal enterprise\n- Established RICO Act application in money laundering prosecutions\n\n3. United States v. Santos (2008)\n- Clarified definitions of money laundering under federal statutes\n- Addressed interpretation of \"proceeds\" in financial crimes\n\n4. Various Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) enforcement actions\n- Established compliance requirements for financial institutions\n- Defined suspicious activity reporting standards\n\n5. HSBC Money Laundering Settlement (2012)\n- $1.9 billion settlement\n- Highlighted international money laundering compliance issues\n\nThese cases demonstrate evolving legal standards for investigating and prosecuting money laundering activities. Each case contributes to understanding regulatory frameworks and enforcement mechanisms.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of money laundering legal precedents?",
